Southeast Asia is an important region to examine and problematize Chineseness. Extant research on Chinese-language advertisements in the early twentieth century mainly focuses on China and Singapore, leaving Indonesian cases underexplored. This study examines how Chinese-language advertisements in late colonial Indonesia constructed Chineseness and imagined their audience. This article utilizes advertisements from anniversary editions of the Kuomintang-affiliated Thien Sung Yit Po (天聲日報) in the Dutch East Indies around 1930. This study argues that the Chineseness constructed in TSYP’s advertisements in late colonial Indonesia was contingent, based on local and transnational sociopolitical and economic context in the late Dutch colony, with hybridity and Chinese modernity intertwined with strategic Chinese nationalism. The findings challenge the essentialized Huaqiao identity disseminated by the Chinese nation-state, highlighting local Chinese agency in late colonial Indonesia.
